The documentary "Francesco Crispi: Making Italians" explores the story of one of the most prominent figures of the Italian Risorgimento, through the voices of historians, scholars, and journalists who retrace his life, analyzing both its highlights and shadows. Conceived and narrated by historian and essayist Giordano Bruno Guerri, the documentary offers an in-depth look at the life of Francesco Crispi (1818-1901), Italy's first true political "star" and the first Prime Minister from Southern Italy-a revolutionary figure with a reckless life: exile, Garibaldian, wanted by police across Europe, burdened with debts, scandals, and even accused of bigamy. But Crispi was also one of the leaders of the 1848 Sicilian Revolution and the key organizer of Garibaldi's Expedition of the Thousand. A multiple-term Minister of the Kingdom of Italy and Prime Minister, his contribution to the birth of the modern state was immense: the abolition of the death penalty, the right to strike, expanded suffrage, and the foundation of a public healthcare system. Understanding the power of communication in the modern age, he was also the first politician to have his own personal newspaper and even a team dedicated to managing his public image. "Italy is made, now we must make Italians" was the motto of the time; and Crispi, for better or worse, embodied it to perfection.

"Tip&Cía" es un documental que intenta reflejar los aspectos más importantes de la personalidad y carrera profesional de Luis Sánchez Pollack. Siendo un personaje tan amplio e imposible de centrar, el programa quiere concentrarse en los aspectos más distintivamente Típicos, y a través de las personas que le conocieron y trabajaron con él intentar mostrar lo que es el misterio del humor de Tip. Para ello nos centraremos en los temas más importantes del humor de Tip (como son la improvisación, su visión del absurdo, sus diferentes parejas artísticas (Top y Coll), sus números más celebres (Mauricita la gamba, el vaso de agua, etc) y los aspectos más interesantes y desconocidos de la vida de Luis Sánchez Polack (sus inicios artísticos como pintor, la muerte de su hijo, su forma de ser). Todo ello aderezado por muchas de las legendarias anécdotas que jalonan la vida del gran humorista, un hombre que derrochaba su humor en su trabajo y en su vida privada porque era un río tan inagotable de talento que no tenía miedo de que se le acabara. Tip&Cía sirve como homenaje de un humorista genial, un creador tan increíblemente lúcido y sincero que lo daba todo cada vez, llegando a la cima de su profesión logrando lo más difícil: hacer que lo más complicado que hay (hacer reír con inteligencia) pareciera lo más fácil del mundo.

With this intention, the film also portrays the multi-ethnic suburbs of Rome in present-day Italy, often regarded as the 'land of immigration,' due to its high population of immigrant residents. True events and stories regarding western immigration have driven us to address this issue in a dramatic, yet ironic, manner. The gradual acceptance of the need to allow asylum to 'political refugees' by the West, has also been accompanied by an increase in the demonization of all who wish to enter the West with hopes of improving their quality of life. Those who, nowadays, are labeled as 'bogus refugees' or 'illegal immigrants,' have not only become the target for short-sighted policies on immigration, but also, victims of deceitful human traffickers. Policies regulating immigration in the West, often based on points systems that evaluate the 'desirability' or 'usefulness' of those requesting transfer, are generally function only for the profit of the host country while these requirements may be entirely ignored for many immigrants whose countries of origin don't qualify as high-risk zones. We will hear these protagonists tell the fascinating stories that accompanied this incredible journey. This documentary will try to give viewers a vivid picture of this colourful reality to give them back a taste of that bygone era. To do that, we will try to recover films, photographs and equipment used at that time and then abandoned on some dusty shelf or jealously kept by some keen aficionado. Open House PGH and the Borland Green Cooperative discuss how their intentional communities share cooking and gardening responsibilities to strengthen their communities. But despite the fascinating developments in the alternative food movement, these emerging opportunities require some amount of privilege and access to food. What happens if your access to healthy food is limited? Just Harvest's Ken Regal, Felicia Lane Savage, and others discuss the history of hunger, posing the widespread issue as a symptom of poverty. After discussing the barriers to accessing food, emergency solutions like food banks and 412 Food Rescue along with longer-term educational efforts like Community Kitchen Pittsburgh and community gardens are surveyed.
